    "historicalContext": "The Lincoln Memorial Arch is part of the Nannie Helen Burroughs School, founded in 1909 by Nannie Helen Burroughs, a prominent African American educator and civil rights leader. The arch was constructed in 1914 to commemorate the 50th anniversary of Abraham Lincoln's death. The school, which educated Black women and girls, was notable for not relying on white donors and for offering a comprehensive curriculum that included academic, vocational, and religious instruction. The site is a National Historic Landmark and reflects the educational and civil rights efforts of Burroughs, who advocated for the empowerment of Black women and girls."
